{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493357"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1298"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1298"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.54,0.02,0.05,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50702"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1298"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3337"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"65"},{"type":"contributions","id":"66"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50702"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old final year University student attends her General Practice requesting medication to help with her \u201cexam nerves\u201d. She is able to function without issue throughout the day, sleeps seven hours a night, eats well, and exercises three times a week. She attends meditation classes and has tried \u201cpositive self-talking\u201d but this has not prevented her anxieties. In practical exams, she says she \u201cfreezes\u201d, gets a dry mouth, palpitations and \u201cmind blank\u201d and feels she will fail. She has previously failed a formative exam. Her upcoming examination is in 3 months\u0027 time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate as first line treatment in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stress relaxation exercises","Cognitive behavioural therapy","Diazepam","Sertraline","Propranolol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis student is presenting with a history of situationally bound anxiety and possible panic attacks. Positive self-talk and meditation are examples of \u003Cstrong\u003Estress relaxation exercises\u003C/strong\u003E; however, she has attempted this to no effect. \u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E would function to reduce sympathetic tone and has been used in the past for the management of performance anxiety, however, there is insufficient evidence of benefit to recommend its use in any anxiety disorders. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E has the potential to cause sedation, which could impair her performance in the exam. \u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E has a role in treating generalised anxiety disorder and panic disorder and although the student does not fulfil full criteria for either disorder, it could be used if her symptoms were more persistent than just related to one exam. Additionally, SSRIs are associated with an initial period of worsened symptoms, particularly in the setting of panic attacks. \u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (CBT) is an appropriate option, and this is first line for many anxiety disorders. This could allow for education and development of cognitive strategies to promote reduction in anxiety symptoms associated with test taking. One meta-analysis has found low quality evidence for the use of CBT in test anxiety, however notes the need for larger trials. The efficacy of CBT in anxiety and related disorders, however, is well supported\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cognitive behavioural therapy is the preferred approach for the management of anxiety disorders and panic attacks."],"references":["Andres, G, Bell, C, Boyce, P, Gale, C, Lampe, L, Marwat, O, Rapee, R, Wilkins, G. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the treatment of panic disorder, social anxiety disorder and generalised anxiety disorder. Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2018; 52(12):1109-1172.","Steenen, S, Wijk, A, Heijden, G, Westrhenen, R, Lange, J, Jongh, A. Propranolol for the treatment of anxiety disorders: Systematic review and meta-analysis. J Psychopharmacol. 2016; 30(2):128-139.","Huntley, C, Young, B, Temple, J, Longworth, M, Smith, C, Jha, V, Fisher, P. The efficacy of interventions for test-anxious university students: A meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. J Anxiety Disord. 2019; 63:36-50.","Kaczkurkin, A. Cognitive-behavioral therapy for anxiety disorders: an update on the empirical evidence. Dialogues Clin Neurosci. 2015; 17(3):337-346.","van Dis, E, van Veen, S, Hagenaars, M. Long-term Outcomes of Cognitive  Behavioral Therapy for Anxiety-Related Disorders A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. JAMA Psychiatry. 2020; 77(3):265-273."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1298"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-16T13:42:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-16T13:42:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"it